The article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama, declaring March 29, 2012, as Vietnam Veterans Day. The proclamation recognizes the service and sacrifices of the more than 3 million Americans who served in the Vietnam War. It pays tribute to those who lost their lives, those who were injured or affected by post-traumatic stress and Agent Orange, and those who returned home to face neglect and mistreatment. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of honoring and showing respect to all veterans and serving them as they served the country. It also calls upon all Americans to observe the day with appropriate programs, ceremonies, and activities to commemorate the 50-year anniversary of the Vietnam War.